english:
  title: A Farewell Letter for Yi Mi-su
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: Long ago, our Sage emerged at the decline of the Zhou dynasty and shared his time with Laozi, becoming mutually instructive to one another. Yet in later generations of scholars, the fault of mutual criticism persisted, and how much more so over more than a thousand years since our Sage's passing? When Buddhism arrived and stood as a third teaching alongside Confucianism and Daoism, their conflict and incompatibility were inevitable. Buddhism takes compassion, expansiveness, stillness, and non-action as its Way, and these have points of accord with the Book of Changes. Should these be unified and harmonized, they share the same ultimate destination. Even if our Sage were to return, he would not reject this. If one seeks to remedy the world's violence, plunder, and destruction of life, only Buddhism's teachings can truly aid in this transformation. Thus even Confucian scholars have come to admire its spirit and follow it. Yet Han Yu alone vigorously opposed it and fiercely contended against it—not because such opposition was unnecessary, but because without it, scholars would fall beyond salvation and Confucianism itself would perish. However, I observe that both Confucian and Buddhist followers today corrupt their own teachings. There are those who don a scholar's robes, speak of benevolence and righteousness, and claim to be followers of Confucius, yet upon closer inspection, they use these teachings to further injustice—committing acts that even the ignorant would hesitate to perform. This is a grave offense against our Sage. Similarly, those with shaven heads wearing monastic robes, abandoning family bonds, indulging in wild fancies, and peddling empty words to seduce others while profiting themselves—are they any different? Should a person of character not reject such corruption and instead praise it to encourage its spread? My criticism of Buddhism lies precisely here, which is why I honor its Way all the more. Mi-su and I are friends, and he delights in Buddhism. I too am pleased to share in this. What troubles me is that he loves to busy himself with worldly affairs, yet whenever he encounters Buddhist monks, he joins palms in reverence and faith. Can this truly be genuine appreciation of Buddhism? I have spoken to him of this before, but to no avail. He regards me simply as one who rejects Buddhism, and fails to understand that I delight in its teachings precisely because I grieve over the indulgence and frivolity of those who corrupt it. Now that he departs to the south, and seeing this parting as weighty, I cannot help but convey this once more—not to change his resolve, but to speak what must be spoken.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han Yu (韓退之) was a famous Tang Dynasty Confucian scholar known for his fierce opposition to Buddhism. Lim Chun references him as an example of necessary criticism.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Way' (道) here refers to the ultimate principle or path in both Confucian and Buddhist philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: The monastic practice of celibacy and renunciation of family ties is referenced critically here as contrary to Confucian values of filial piety and family continuity.
